"1580–Overleden","about 1580":"circa 1580","1612":"1612","5 Aug 1828":"5 augustus 1828","1580":"1580","Gainsborough, Lincolnshire, England":"Gainsborough, Lincolnshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Gainsborough, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Gainsborough, Lincolnshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1580–":"about 1580–Deceased","1580–Female":"1580–Deceased","1612–Female":"1612–Deceased","1580–Male":"1580–Deceased","about 1580":"about 1580","1612":"1612","5 Aug 1828":"5 August 1828","1580":"1580","Gainsborough, Lincolnshire, England":"Gainsborough, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Gainsborough, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Gainsborough, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Markham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Markham Clinton or East Markham (Nottinghamshire). The placename derives from Old English <i>mearc</i> ‘mark, boundary’ + <i>hām</i> ‘village, homestead’ or <i>hamm</i> ‘water meadow’.","Irish: English surname used as an equivalent of Gaelic <b>Ó Marcacháin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Marcachán</i>’, a diminutive of <i>Marcach</i> ‘horseman, rider’ (see   Markey  ). This was originally a Galway surname but is now found mainly in Clare, sometimes translated into English as   Ryder  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Markey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Donal, Donovan, Fergal.","Irish (Monaghan): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Marcaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Marcach</i>’, a name meaning ‘horseman, knight’, from <i>marc</i> ‘horse’. Compare   Markham   2.","English: apparently from a placename meaning ‘boundary river’ in Old or Middle English, but no such place has been identified."]},{"name":"Markum","meanings":["Altered form of English   Markham  ."]},{"name":"Marcum","meanings":["Altered form of English   Markham  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Markham was born about 1580, in England, United Kingdom. He married Sarah Ashley on 5 August 1828, in Gainsborough, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1580–":"umbes 1580–Surnud","1580–Female":"1580–Surnud","1612–Female":"1612–Surnud","1580–Male":"1580–Surnud","about 1580":"umbes 1580","1612":"1612","5 Aug 1828":"5. august 1828","1580":"1580","Gainsborough, Lincolnshire, England":"Gainsborough, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Gainsborough, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Gainsborough, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1580–":"noin 1580–Kuollut","1580–Female":"1580–Kuollut","1612–Female":"1612–Kuollut","1580–Male":"1580–Kuollut","about 1580":"noin 1580","1612":"1612","5 Aug 1828":"5. elokuuta 1828","1580":"1580","Gainsborough, Lincolnshire, England":"Gainsborough, Lincolnshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Gainsborough, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Gainsborough, Lincolnshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1580–":"environ 1580–Décédé","